      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Exposing Medical Mistakes'' (editorial, Feb. 24):</p>
        <p>It is likely that Washington and the states will remain mired in the decades-long battle with hospitals and doctors who, concerned with profits, fear mandatory public disclosure of medical errors. It would be better if medical consumers were provided with the means to protect themselves.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Exposing Medical Mistakes'' (editorial, Feb. 24):</p>
        <p>It is likely that Washington and the states will remain mired in the decades-long battle with hospitals and doctors who, concerned with profits, fear mandatory public disclosure of medical errors. It would be better if medical consumers were provided with the means to protect themselves.</p>
        <p>As a first step, all patients should have access to the taxpayer-financed National Practitioners' Data Bank and any other doctor-specific information that can be culled from state medical board records. It is time that all patients had the right to make truly informed decisions about their care.</p>
        <p>LAURA WITTKIN  Yonkers, Feb. 26, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a former executive director of the National Center for Patients' Rights.</p>
      </block>
